                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    ALT can be helpful for anyone experiencing hearing
                    challenges—whether you have mild hearing loss or use hearing
                    aids or cochlear implants. The right solution depends on
                    your hearing needs and the environments where you need
                    support.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    What are assistive listening devices (ALDs)?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    ALDs are personal devices designed to improve communication
                    in small group settings or one-on-one conversations. They
                    typically include a microphone for the speaker and a
                    receiver or amplifier to help the listener hear more
                    clearly. They’re especially useful in noisy places or for
                    direct communication.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    What are assistive listening technologies (ALTs)?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    ALTs are designed for use in larger public spaces, such as
                    theaters, places of worship, airports, or lecture halls.
                    They capture sound from a microphone or sound system and
                    send it directly to hearing aids, cochlear implants,
                    receivers worn by the listener, or digital devices like
                    phones. These systems minimize background noise and improve
                    clarity.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    What are the main types of assistive listening systems?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    The three primary ALS technologies are:<br />
                    <strong>Hearing loops:</strong> Use magnetic fields to transmit
                    sound to hearing aids or cochlear implants with a telecoil setting.<br
                    />
                    <strong>FM or DM systems:</strong> Use radio signals to transmit
                    sound from a source to personal receivers, often used in classrooms
                    or meetings.<br />
                    <strong>Infrared (IR) systems:</strong> Use light waves to send
                    sound to a receiver. These require a clear line of sight and
                    are often used in settings like cinemas or conference rooms.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">How do hearing loops work?</div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    A hearing loop system sends audio directly into a hearing
                    aid or cochlear implant via a magnetic signal. Users must
                    switch their device to the "T" (telecoil) setting to receive
                    the signal. Hearing loops are commonly found in theaters,
                    auditoriums, and other public venues.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    What is a personal infrared loop system?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    This system uses infrared light to wirelessly send sound to
                    a portable receiver worn around the neck. The receiver has a
                    built-in loop that sends the audio directly to a hearing
                    aid’s telecoil. These are often available in classrooms or
                    lecture halls.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    Are there smartphone apps that help with hearing?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Yes. Many mobile apps offer features such as real-time
                    captioning, sound amplification, or audio streaming. Some
                    are designed to work with hearing aids or implants, while
                    others function independently to improve listening in
                    specific environments.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    Can phones work with assistive listening technology?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Yes. By law, phones must be compatible with hearing aids.
                    Most modern smartphones, including iPhones and Androids,
                    offer either <strong>acoustic coupling</strong> (amplifies surrounding
                    and phone audio) or <strong>telecoil compatibility</strong> (direct
                    connection for clearer sound without background noise). Ask your
                    audiologist if your device’s telecoil feature is activated.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    Do I still need assistive listening devices if I use hearing
                    aids?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Possibly. While hearing aids offer excellent amplification,
                    they may not always be enough—especially in noisy
                    environments or public venues. ALDs and ALSs complement your
                    hearing aids by providing clearer sound in specific
                    settings.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    How do these technologies help in daily life?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Assistive listening tools make activities like attending
                    religious services, watching movies, riding public
                    transport, or participating in meetings more accessible.
                    They reduce listening fatigue, improve comprehension, and
                    help users feel more connected and independent.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    Are public venues required to offer assistive listening
                    systems?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    In many countries, yes. Laws such as the Americans with
                    Disabilities Act (ADA) in the U.S., the UK Equality Act
                    2010, and Australia’s Disability Discrimination Act require
                    public facilities to provide ALS options for people with
                    hearing loss.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    Are there standards for assistive listening systems?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Yes. International standards like <strong>IEC60118-4</strong
                    > ensure that systems—especially hearing loops—are properly installed
                    and effective. These regulations promote high-quality experiences
                    and prevent low-performance installations that fail to meet users’
                    needs.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">Which type of system is best?</div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    It depends on the environment and the user’s preferences.
                    Hearing loops are widely favored by users for their
                    simplicity and effectiveness, but FM, DM, and IR systems
                    also offer benefits in specific settings. A hearing care
                    professional can help determine what suits your needs best.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="expandable-single">
                <div class="expandable-top">
                  <div class="text-h5">
                    How do assistive listening systems work with hearing aids?
                  </div>
                  <div class="faq-animated-box">
                    <div class="faq-horizontal"></div>
                    <div class="faq-vertical"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="expandable-bottom">
                  <p class="faq-paragraph">
                    Most systems transmit sound directly to hearing aids using a
                    telecoil or Bluetooth feature. If your device has a
                    telecoil, connecting to a hearing loop is often as simple as
                    switching to the "T" setting. Otherwise, a neckloop or
                    dedicated receiver may be needed.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
